<br>
NORFORK -- Producers of a new TV fly-fishing series are looking for the most skilled anglers in America, and a Norfork fishing guide is in the running. <br>
<br>
Fishing guide John B. Gulley has been selected to compete in the southeast qualifier for the 2003 Fly Fishing Masters Tournament. The southeast qualifier will be Sept. 20-21 in Atlanta, Ga., for casting and Sept. 23-24 at Helen, Ga., for fishing. <br>
<br>
From the field of 200 fly-fishing teams in four regional casting competitions, 32 teams will advance to the fishing competition. Then, four regional teams will advance to the national finals at an undisclosed location in October. The four final teams will be judged and ranked first through fourth according to performance. <br>
<br>
The top ranked two-person team will receive a cash prize of $30,000, with the fourth ranking team winning $2,000. The tournament is being produced for incorporation into a new television series called &quot;Fly Fishing Masters&quot; for initial broadcast on the Outdoor Life Network, which is carried by Cox Communications in this area as Channel 61. <br>
<br>
Gulley is an award-winning fishing guide and conservationist. He was chosen by the Orvis company as &quot;Guide of the Year&quot; in 1998 and remains one of two Orvis-endorsed fly- fishing guides in Arkansas. <br>
<br>
Gulley, who has nearly 30 years' experience guiding on Ozark streams, was named Arkansas Water Conservationist of the Year in May by the Arkansas Wildlife Federation and other sponsors of the award. He operates his own fly-fishing service and instructs others in fly fishing. <br>
<br>
To learn more, visit Gulley's Web site at www.flyguide.com<br>
